liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Inflation has risen by 1.2% in the three months to September, beating market expectations of a 1.1% rise. Annual inflation, however, fell to 5.4%, down from 6% for the 12 months prior. The ABS says automotive fuel, electricity and rents were the biggest contributors to inflation rising during the quarter.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: BREAKING: Inflation jumps by 1.2 per cent in September quarter, driven by rising fuel prices

children.content: Inflation has risen by 1.2% in the three months to September, beating market expectations of a 1.1% rise.
Annual inflation, however, fell to 5.4%, down from 6% for the 12 months prior.
The ABS says automotive fuel, electricity and rents were the biggest contributors to inflation rising during the quarter.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: It's not just us waiting for the inflation data to come out in just under 15 minutes' time â€” the RBA is also keeping watch as it considers a 13th rate rise at its Melbourne Cup Day meeting. Markets are generally expecting a 1.1% headline rise in the September quarter, taking the annual reading to 5.3%. But what would the reading need to be if the RBA were to take the leap with another rate hike? Former RBA staffer, now Challenger chief economist, Jonathan Kearns told The Business that rising oil prices is a wildcard and risks increasing inflation expectations â€” and if today's quarterly inflation figure is higher than 1.2%, we'll be "in trouble". liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The local share market has opened higher this morning, up 0.5% to 6,889 points as of 10:40am AEDT. (For live figures at any time, head to the top of the blog.) Sector-wise, miners are leading the charge, with basic materials the best performer so far ( +1.8% ). Other sectors in positive territory so far include consumer cyclicals (+0.7%), technology (+0.7%), academic and educational services (+0.6%) and industrials (+0.3%). At the other end, health care and real estate are down 0.4% each, as are utilities (-0.3%) and consumer non-cyclicals (-0.1%). Rounding out the sectors, energy and financials are both flat. As for the top movers, Ampol is seeing the most movement so far today after reporting bumper earnings for the third quarter. Meanwhile, Magellan has suffered the biggest loss so far, after CEO David George announced his exit from the company. The top five performers so far: Ampol +4.5% Kelsian Group +4% Telix Pharmaceuticals +3.8% Lynas Rare Earths +3.8% Sayona Mining +3.7% And the bottom five movers: Magellan Financial -4.3% Capricorn Metals -3.1% Karoon Energy -2.9% Genesis Minerals -2.8% Neuren Pharmaceuticals -2.7%
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX opens higher as miners rally, Magellan down as CEO departs
